Overleden","1362–1422":"1362–1422","1388–1446":"1388–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Overleden","1446":"1446","Abt 1366":"circa 1366","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1362":"1362","about 1388":"circa 1388","Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Drakestown, County Meath, Ierland","Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland":"Drakestown, County Meath, Ierland"},"en":{"Abt 1366–":"about 1366–Deceased","1362–1422":"1362–1422","1388–1446":"1388–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Deceased","1446":"1446","Abt 1366":"about 1366","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1362":"1362","about 1388":"about 1388","Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland","Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland":"Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>drake</i>, either ‘drake, male duck’ (compare   Duck  ) or ‘dragon’ (Old English <i>draca</i> ‘snake, dragon’ or the cognate Old Norse <i>draki</i>), including an emblematic dragon on a flag (compare   Dragon  ). Both the Old English and the Old Norse forms are from Latin <i>draco</i> ‘snake, monster’; its sense as a nickname is unclear but it may have had the sense ‘standard bearer’. The name was taken to Ireland in the 13th century and reinforced by later English settlers in the 17th century.","German: from Low German <i>drake</i> ‘dragon’, familiar as image on signboards, hence a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn with such signboard.","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized and Flemish, of <b>Draak</b>, a cognate of 2 above, from <i>draak</i> (Middle Dutch <i>drake</i>) ‘dragon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Drakes","meanings":["English: variant of   Drake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Drax (Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>dræg</i> ‘portage, place where boats are dragged’ or <i>dræg</i> ‘drag net’, influenced by Old Norse <i>drag</i> ‘portage’, with a plural <i>drages</i> being shortened to <i>drags</i>, <i>Drax</i>.","In some cases perhaps an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) cognate in some other language."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Reduced form of Old Norse <i>Þorfriðr</i>, from <i>Þórr</i> (  see  Tor  ) + <i>friðr</i> ‘peace’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Lord John Drake was born about 1366, in Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland. She had at least 1 daughter with Lord John Drake."},"et":{"Abt 1366–":"umbes 1366–Surnud","1362–1422":"1362–1422","1388–1446":"1388–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1446":"1446","Abt 1366":"umbes 1366","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1362":"1362","about 1388":"umbes 1388","Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Drakestown, County Meath, Iirimaa","Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland":"Drakestown, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1366–":"noin 1366–Kuollut","1362–1422":"1362–1422","1388–1446":"1388–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Kuollut","1446":"1446","Abt 1366":"noin 1366","1422":"1422","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1362":"1362","about 1388":"noin 1388","Drakestown, County Meat